Colnew

Colnew is a program to solve a system of differential equations with
boundary conditions by the collocation method. This means the interval
on which the system is defined is subdivided in subintervals by a
mesh.  On each subinterval one approximates the solution by
splines. The differential equations are imposed on gaussian points
inside the subintervals, while at their boundaries, on the mesh, one
imposes continuity of the derivatives of lower order. This gives a big
system of algebraic equations on the coefficients of the splines which
is solved simply in the linear case and by Newton methods in the non
linear case. From this one computes the z-vector at each point, that
is the values of the mstar lower order derivatives obtained from the
splines.  Eventually the mesh is refined until one is satisfied of the
solution.

Define the parameters which enter your equations, and the interval
aleft, aright on which they are defined, except those you want to use
for continuation, if necessary. In general most parameters must be
defined as floating point values, the system enforces that for the
basic ones. Failing to do that, you will see lisp errors. You will
also see a lisp error before computing the mesh if you have forgotten
to define aleft or aright or if you don't have aleft < aright.  Then
issue a depends([<functions>],<var>) so that you can write the
differential equations in the form: diff(u,x,n) = f(functions of lower
order derivatives). Without the depends declaration all derivatives
will vanish, and nothing works.

list_of_eqns:
Colnew only accepts systems where the higher order derivatives can be
expressed explicitly. To be able to parse things simply, only use the
notation diff(u,x,m) even for m=1, and not diff(u(x),x,m).  In general
if the higher orders are n_i then the solution of the system depends
on mstar=sum n_i constants. Put the equations in a list list_of_eqns.

list_of_conds:
To fix a solution one must provide precisely mstar conditions, either
at the boundary or even inside the interval [aleft,aright]. Each
condition must be of the form C(p)=0 where C is some function of the
lower order derivatives and C must vanish at the point p. The points p
form an ordered list ZETA of length mstar. Those which are interior to
the interval are taken uniquely as elements of the ordered array
fixpnt, to which one may add other interior points. The aim is that
all points of fixpoint belong to the computation mesh, thus the
differential equations is not checked on them, which allows in
particular to avoid singularities. Put the conditions in the list
list_of_conds. One may edit fxpoint later.

The Example 4 is a case where the differential equation is singular at
the 3 points aleft, aright, and the one interior point a_2 of
fixpnt. The boundary conditions are imposed on these 3 points
a_j. They are of the unusual type, with some constant k,
(diff(p,t,1)-k*p)(a_j)=0 plus a normalization p(a_2)-1=0. These
singularities do not preclude finding perfectly fine solutions obeying
the boundary conditions.

list_of_guess:
In general the considered systems have several discrete solutions
fulfilling both equations and boundary conditions. To select and
converge on a particular one, it is necessary to provide a guess as
starting point.  This is a list of functions of the variable
corresponding to the underived functions of the system. For example
give a guess for G(x) and H(x) in Example 3.  The system uses maxima
to compute their appropriate derivatives. Put the guess of functions
in the list list_of_guess. So this is a list of explicit functions of
the variable.
 
tolerances:
At each step of the refinement on has a z-vector defined at each point
of each subinterval.  One may chose to check only particular
components, for example for [G,G',H,H',H''] giving [z1,z2,z3,z4,z5],
if one wants to look only at G and H, that is z1 and z3, one defines
ntol=2, ltol=[1,3]. One may also require values for the corresponding
tolerances, for example tol=[1d-7,1d-7].  By default the system checks
tolerances on all mstar components, with tolerance values
1d-5. Otherwise one needs to set ntol to a smaller value at the
beginning. The meaning of the tolerance eps is that, on each
subinterval, one tries to get, for all checked zj that |zj -zj^0| <
eps + eps*zj^0, where zj^0 is supposed to be the exact solution, of
course estimated from the convergence of the refined approximations.

ipar:
After having parsed the equations and conditions the system outputs the
many colnew variables that it has discovered, in particular the array
ipar of 11 integers that controls colnew behavior. In most case one
should not have to modify it, but one may consult the documentation of
colnew_package if necessary. After that the system outputs a break
which allows to perform modifications of ipar, ltol, tol, fixpnt if
one so desires. For example for Example 3 one inserts ltol:[1,3]$
tol:[1d-7,1d-7]$ at the prompt. One terminates the break by typing
exit; at the prompt. One should check that all displayed values are
reasonable and contain numerical data. If the problem is linear one should
set ipar[1]:0 which simplifies the solution of the collocation problem.
One could set ipar[7] to have more or less colnew verbosity. It may be
necessary to increase ipar[2] and ipar[3] for numerically difficult problems,
see the example osc2.mac.

use_result:
Define the function use_result() which does the most basic things with
the result of colnew. Basically one calls colnew_appsln(xx, mstar,
fspace, ispace) where xx is an array of points, perhaps just one,
chosen as we like, and the result is the array of all zj values at
these points, so the result is a 2-dim array. For example in Example 3
xx is an array of 100 points covering the whole interval, and we are
interested only on the first component of the z-vector (that is G),
while in Example 4 xx is an array of just one point [0.2] and we are
interested in just f2 and f4, that is the components 3 and 4 of the
z-vector. Then store the chosen components somewhere. The function
run_colnew() runs colnew, followed by use_result. Finally produce, for
example, a plot from the stored results.


continuation:
In the simplest case all parameters are fixed to numerical values at
the beginning. Then colnew will find the solution starting from the
guess. In many interesting cases there are parameters that one can
vary from computation to computation, the previous result serving as
guess for the following one. To do that, after the first computation
one has to set ipar[9]:3 ipar[3]:ispace[1]. The system will do it
automatically. The function run_colnew executes in a context where the
free parameters have been given numerical values, such as s,L in Example 3
or v in Example 4, this ensures that the functions fsub, etc. are
evaluated with these values of the parameters. One can check that by
issuing:
dispfun(fsub,dfsub,gsub,dgsub)
after their definitions in colnew_help.mac. They should contain only
numerical values besides the zj.  The examples Example 3 and Example 4
show how to do the continuation. If some parameters are not evaluated as
numerical values you will see lisp errors saying that some quantity is not
a floating point value.
